WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:16.039 --> 00:00:19.039
Hello, thank you for clicking on my video.

00:00:19.039 --> 00:00:23.920
I’m Xiaoxuan, and in this episode, I’ll continue unboxing DVDs I brought back from Japan to Toronto.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.960
This is a limited-edition “Sakamoto Ryuichi BTTB Box Set” released in 1999.

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:32.039
I found this second-hand set at Tokyo's Disk Union music store.

00:00:32.039 --> 00:00:36.039
Japanese second-hand CDs are usually well-preserved.

00:00:36.039 --> 00:00:46.800
Apart from the box having a slightly musty smell, everything inside is about 80% new.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:56.079
When I opened it for the first time, I was shocked to find a 3.5-inch floppy disk inside.

00:00:56.079 --> 00:00:59.920
It contains MIDI data played by Sakamoto Ryuichi.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:04.000
It can be used on any device equipped with MIDI functionality.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.840
The official recommendation is to use a YAMAHA MU100 or similar device

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:11.880
to more accurately reproduce the performance effects of the “Professor.”

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:32.639
Many friends left comments last time asking if I recommend this MUJI CD player.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:40.840
So this time, I’ll let you hear the noise it makes when playing a CD.

00:01:41.639 --> 00:01:49.519
See if you can accept it—this mechanical noise persists while listening to music.

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:57.000
The current volume is around Volume 20.

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:06.000
Now, let’s hear how it sounds at maximum volume.

00:02:16.719 --> 00:02:22.800
Even at maximum volume, the physical noise cannot be masked.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:29.320
Feel free to leave a comment—do you think this 14,900-yen CD player is worth it?

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:38.519
Due to copyright issues, I’ll stop the test here. Let’s continue with the unboxing.

00:02:39.599 --> 00:02:43.599
This second-hand first-edition limited box set

00:02:43.599 --> 00:02:47.719
still has the original shrink-wrap label from 1999.

00:02:47.719 --> 00:02:52.639
It shows the pricing and detailed information from back then.

00:02:52.639 --> 00:02:55.719
It inspired me to save the shrink-wrap labels

00:02:55.719 --> 00:03:02.599
when I unbox Criterion Collection DVDs next time and keep them in the box.

00:03:03.599 --> 00:03:07.480
It feels like the person who originally bought this album

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:11.639
must have been a hardcore fan of the Professor.

00:03:11.639 --> 00:03:17.760
There’s even a magazine clipping from 1999 inside.

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:25.480
It mentions the release date, November 26, 1999, and the price.

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:42.199
Here’s another magazine interview and introduction about this album.

00:03:42.199 --> 00:03:51.760
The Professor’s style and outfit instantly take you back to 1999.

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:06.360
At the bottom of the page, you can see the magazine’s name and year information:

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:10.599
"Yahoo! Internet Guide," January 1999 issue, page 99.

00:04:11.599 --> 00:04:16.119
And now, for the highlight of this box set!

00:04:16.119 --> 00:04:22.360
The sheet music for 8 tracks corresponding to the 3.5-inch floppy disk data.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:32.199
Over 20 years have passed since November 1999, and the adhesive tape has deteriorated.

00:04:33.199 --> 00:04:38.639
I will also release an exclusive “pure” version of this unboxing episode.

00:04:38.639 --> 00:04:44.280
It will include an unedited, single-shot unboxing video showing every page of the sheet music.

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:48.400
Since it’s quite long, I won’t include it in the main video.

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:55.239
For those interested, feel free to check out the “pure” version later.

00:04:55.239 --> 00:05:00.679
The “pure” version includes the sheet music for 8 tracks and samples of 14 songs (20 seconds each).

00:05:01.679 --> 00:05:06.840
Thank you for watching this far—here comes the bonus content.

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:13.159
About Tokyo’s second-hand CD stores and more CDs I found.

00:05:14.159 --> 00:05:18.480
This Sakamoto Ryuichi album was bought at Disk Union in Jinbocho, Tokyo.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:25.039
The store is very small, so I couldn’t film there.

00:05:26.039 --> 00:05:30.480
Later, I also visited the classical store at Ochanomizu’s Disk Union.

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:33.480
Disk Union has many branches, and prices are quite affordable.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:37.079
Underneath the Uplink Cinema in Kichijoji, Tokyo,

00:05:37.079 --> 00:05:39.199
there’s also a Disk Union store.

00:05:39.199 --> 00:05:40.840
This branch is a mixed-type store.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:44.559
Besides CDs, they also sell second-hand vinyl and even new vinyl records.

00:05:44.559 --> 00:05:48.800
I found many second-hand CDs there, priced around 800 yen—less than 10 CAD.

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:52.639
Only the "Drive My Car" CD was bought new at Tower Records.

00:05:52.639 --> 00:05:55.519
If it were a new vinyl record, it would probably cost 50–100 CAD.

00:05:55.519 --> 00:05:57.559
These Joe Hisaishi CDs were just a few hundred yen.

00:05:57.559 --> 00:06:01.760
In contrast to the rare Eiko Ishibashi albums, CDs by Yoko Kanno are everywhere in music stores.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:05.159
I found CDs for "Cowboy Bebop," "Memories Trilogy," and "Ghost in the Shell."

00:06:05.159 --> 00:06:09.079
There were also more childhood-memory film soundtracks.

00:06:09.079 --> 00:06:11.320
I even bought two soundtracks for "Evangelion."

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:14.719
Does anyone remember the TV song “Brave young boy, go create miracles”?

00:06:14.719 --> 00:06:18.159
I even got two “Sailor Moon” soundtracks (showing my age here).

00:06:18.639 --> 00:06:21.199
Thank you for watching this far.

00:06:21.199 --> 00:06:24.320
It’s a new year, a new start.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:26.800
Here, I’m setting a goal to update at least bi-weekly.

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.239
This year, I’ll create more exclusive videos from the footage I shoot

00:06:30.239 --> 00:06:34.440
for friends who are interested in collecting.

